The general linear group, often denoted as [GL](Group_(mathematics))<sub>n</sub>(F) or GL(n, F), is the grand assembly of all [n × n invertible matrices](Invertible_matrix) that operate under the familiar rules of [matrix multiplication](Matrix_multiplication). It’s a group, you see, because the product of any two matrices that can be inverted will itself be invertible, and the inverse of an invertible matrix is, naturally, also invertible. The [identity matrix](Identity_matrix) sits at the head of this operation as the neutral element. The name "general linear" isn't just for show; it arises from the fact that the columns (and rows, for that matter) of such matrices are [linearly independent](Linearly_independent). This means they transform points in [general linear position](General_linear_position) to other points that remain in that same, well, general linear position.

Now, the specifics of what populates these matrices matter. For instance, the general linear group over the [real numbers](Real_numbers), denoted GL<sub>n</sub>(ℝ) or GL(n, ℝ), is comprised of n × n invertible matrices with real entries. More broadly, for any [field](Field_(mathematics)) F – and yes, that includes the [complex numbers](Complex_number) – or any [ring](Ring_(mathematics)) R, like the humble [integers](Integer), the general linear group consists of n × n invertible matrices whose entries hail from F or R, respectively. The notation GL(n, F) or GL<sub>n</sub>(F) is standard, often simplified to GL(n) if the field is implicitly understood.

We can also speak of the general linear group of a vector space, GL(V), which is the [automorphism group](Automorphism_group) – the collection of all [bijective](Bijective) [linear transformations](Linear_transformation) from V to itself, composed under function composition. If V has a finite [dimension](Hamel_dimension) n, then GL(V) is [isomorphic](Group_isomorphism) to GL(n, F), though this isomorphism is not absolute; it hinges on the choice of a [basis](Basis_(linear_algebra)) for V. When a basis {e<sub>1</sub>, ..., e<sub>n</sub>} is selected, an automorphism T in GL(V) can be represented by a matrix whose entries a<sub>ji</sub> are determined by how T acts on each basis vector: T(e<sub>i</sub>) = Σ<sub>j=1</sub><sup>n</sup> a<sub>ji</sub>e<sub>j</sub>.

For a [commutative ring](Commutative_ring) R, GL(n, R) can be seen as the group of automorphisms of a free R-module of rank n. One can define GL(M) for any R-module M, but it won't always be isomorphic to GL(n, R).

### Determinants and Invertibility

The connection to determinants is crucial. Over a field F, a matrix is invertible precisely when its [determinant](Determinant) is non-zero. So, GL(n, F) can be viewed as the set of n × n matrices with non-zero determinants. When dealing with a commutative ring R, invertibility of a matrix is tied to its determinant being a [unit](Unit_(ring_theory)) in R – meaning, it has a multiplicative inverse within R. Thus, GL(n, R) comprises matrices whose determinants are units. For non-commutative rings, determinants are less straightforward, and GL(n, R) is defined as the [unit group](Unit_group) of the [matrix ring](Matrix_ring) M(n, R).

### Lie Group Structure

#### Real Case

The general linear group GL(n, ℝ) over the [real numbers](Real_number) is a real [Lie group](Lie_group) with a dimension of n². This stems from the fact that the space of all n × n real matrices, M<sub>n</sub>(ℝ), is a [real vector space](Real_vector_space) of dimension n². GL(n, ℝ) is the subset of these matrices with non-zero determinants. Since the determinant is a [polynomial](Polynomial) function, GL(n, ℝ) forms an [open affine subvariety](Algebraic_variety) of M<sub>n</sub>(ℝ), and thus a [smooth manifold](Smooth_manifold) of the same dimension.

The [Lie algebra](Lie_algebra) associated with GL(n, ℝ), denoted 𝔤𝔩<sub>n</sub>, is the set of all n × n real matrices, with the [commutator](Commutator) acting as the Lie bracket.

As a manifold, GL(n, ℝ) isn't a single piece; it's split into two [connected components](Connected_space): one for matrices with positive determinants and one for those with negative determinants. The [identity component](Identity_component), GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ), comprises matrices with positive determinants. This component is also a Lie group of dimension n² and shares the same Lie algebra as GL(n, ℝ).

The [polar decomposition](Polar_decomposition) reveals a homeomorphism between GL(n, ℝ) and the product of the [orthogonal group](Orthogonal_group) O(n) with the set of positive-definite symmetric matrices. Similarly, GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ) is homeomorphic to the product of the [special orthogonal group](Special_orthogonal_group) SO(n) and the same set of positive-definite symmetric matrices. Because this latter set is contractible, the [fundamental group](Fundamental_group) of GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ) is isomorphic to that of SO(n).

This homeomorphism also confirms that GL(n, ℝ) is [noncompact](Compact_space). Its [maximal compact subgroup](Maximal_compact_subgroup) is the orthogonal group O(n), while for GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ), it’s the special orthogonal group SO(n). Much like SO(n), GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ) isn't [simply connected](Simply_connected) (unless n=1); its fundamental group is isomorphic to ℤ for n=2 and ℤ<sub>2</sub> for n>2.

#### Complex Case

The general linear group over the [complex numbers](Complex_number), GL(n, ℂ), is a complex [Lie group](Lie_group) with complex dimension n². As a real Lie group, its dimension doubles to 2n². The real matrix group GL(n, ℝ) embeds within it, forming a real Lie subgroup. These inclusions, GL(n, ℝ) < GL(n, ℂ) < GL(2n, ℝ), correspond to real dimensions n², 2n², and 4n², respectively. Complex n-dimensional matrices can be identified with real 2n-dimensional matrices that preserve a [linear complex structure](Linear_complex_structure) – that is, they commute with a matrix J such that J² = -I, where J represents multiplication by the imaginary unit i.

The [Lie algebra](Lie_algebra) of GL(n, ℂ) consists of all n × n complex matrices, with the Lie bracket defined by the [commutator](Commutator).

Unlike its real counterpart, GL(n, ℂ) is [connected](Connected_space). This is partly due to the multiplicative group of complex numbers, ℂ<sup>×</sup>, being connected. GL(n, ℂ) is not compact; its [maximal compact subgroup](Maximal_compact_subgroup) is the [unitary group](Unitary_group) U(n). And, similar to U(n), GL(n, ℂ) is not [simply connected](Simply_connected), possessing a [fundamental group](Fundamental_group) isomorphic to ℤ.

#### Over Finite Fields

When F is a [finite field](Finite_field) with q elements, the notation GL(n, q) is often used. For a prime p, GL(n, p) represents the [outer automorphism group](Outer_automorphism_group) of the group ℤ<sub>p</sub><sup>n</sup>, and also its automorphism group, as ℤ<sub>p</sub><sup>n</sup> is abelian, rendering the [inner automorphism group](Inner_automorphism_group) trivial.

The order of GL(n, q) is given by:

$$ \prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(q^{n}-q^{k})=(q^{n}-1)(q^{n}-q)(q^{n}-q^{2})\ \cdots \ (q^{n}-q^{n-1}). $$

This can be derived by counting the possible columns: the first column can be any non-zero vector; the second, any vector not in the span of the first; and so on. In q-analog notation, this is [n]<sub>q</sub>! (q-1)<sup>n</sup> q<sup>n choose 2</sup>.

For instance, GL(3, 2) has an order of (8 − 1)(8 − 2)(8 − 4) = 168. This group is the automorphism group of the [Fano plane](Fano_plane) and of the group ℤ<sub>2</sub><sup>3</sup>. It is also isomorphic to [PSL(2, 7)](/PSL(2,7)). These formulas relate to the counting of points on [Grassmannians](Grassmannian) over F, essentially counting subspaces of a given dimension. This connection to [Schubert decomposition](Schubert_decomposition) and q-analogs of [Betti numbers](Betti_number) was a hint towards the [Weil conjectures](Weil_conjectures).

Interestingly, in the limit as q approaches 1, the order of GL(n, q) appears to go to zero. However, with proper normalization (dividing by (q-1)<sup>n</sup>), it converges to the order of the [symmetric group](Symmetric_group) S<sub>n</sub>. This has led to the philosophical interpretation in the context of the [field with one element](Field_with_one_element) where S<sub>n</sub> is seen as GL(n, 1).

#### History

The general linear group over a prime field, GL(ν, p), and its order were first described by [Évariste Galois](/%C3%89variste_Galois) in 1832, in his final letter. He used this in his work on the [Galois group](Galois_group) of the general equation of degree p<sup>ν</sup>.

### Special Linear Group

The [special linear group](Special_linear_group), SL(n, F), consists of matrices with a determinant of precisely 1. These matrices are distinguished by satisfying a polynomial equation, det(A) = 1, placing them on an [algebraic variety](Algebraic_variety). The determinant property ensures that the product of two matrices with determinant 1 also has determinant 1, forming a group.

The determinant function, det: GL(n, F) → F<sup>×</sup> (where F<sup>×</sup> is the [multiplicative group](Multiplicative_group) of F), is a [group homomorphism](Group_homomorphism). It is surjective, and its [kernel](Kernel_(algebra)) is the special linear group SL(n, F). Consequently, SL(n, F) is a [normal subgroup](Normal_subgroup) of GL(n, F). By the [first isomorphism theorem](First_isomorphism_theorem), the quotient group GL(n, F) / SL(n, F) is isomorphic to F<sup>×</sup>. In fact, GL(n, F) can be expressed as a [semidirect product](Semidirect_product): GL(n, F) = SL(n, F) ⋉ F<sup>×</sup>.

For a field or [division ring](Division_ring) F, the special linear group is the [derived group](Derived_group) (or commutator subgroup) of GL(n, F), provided n ≠ 2 or F is not the [field with two elements](Finite_field).

When F is ℝ or ℂ, SL(n, F) is a [Lie subgroup](Lie_subgroup) of GL(n, F) with dimension n² - 1. Its [Lie algebra](Lie_algebra) comprises n × n matrices over F with a [trace](Trace_(matrix)) of zero, the Lie bracket being the [commutator](Commutator).

SL(n, ℝ) can be characterized as the group of [volume](Volume)- and [orientation-preserving](Orientation-preserving) linear transformations of ℝ<sup>n</sup>.

SL(n, ℂ) is simply connected, whereas SL(n, ℝ) is not. The fundamental group of SL(n, ℝ) mirrors that of GL<sup>+</sup>(n, ℝ), being ℤ for n=2 and ℤ<sub>2</sub> for n>2.

### Other Subgroups

#### Diagonal Subgroups

The set of invertible [diagonal matrices](Diagonal_matrix) forms a subgroup of GL(n, F) isomorphic to (F<sup>×</sup>)<sup>n</sup>. In fields like ℝ and ℂ, these represent scaling operations. Scalar matrices, which are constant multiples of the identity matrix, form a subgroup isomorphic to F<sup>×</sup>. This subgroup constitutes the [center](Center_of_a_group) of GL(n, F), making it a normal, abelian subgroup. The center of SL(n, F) consists of scalar matrices with determinant 1, isomorphic to the group of n<sup>th</sup> [roots of unity](Roots_of_unity) in F.

#### Classical Groups

The [classical groups](Classical_group) are subgroups of GL(V) that preserve specific [bilinear forms](Bilinear_form) on a vector space V. These include:
* The [orthogonal group](Orthogonal_group), O(V), which preserves a [non-degenerate](Non-degenerate) [quadratic form](Quadratic_form) on V.
* The [symplectic group](Symplectic_group), Sp(V), which preserves a [symplectic form](Symplectic_vector_space) on V (a non-degenerate [alternating form](Alternating_form)).
* The [unitary group](Unitary_group), U(V), which, over ℂ, preserves a non-degenerate [hermitian form](Hermitian_form) on V.

These groups are significant examples of Lie groups.

### Related Groups and Monoids

#### Projective Linear Group

The [projective linear group](Projective_linear_group), PGL(n, F), and the [projective special linear group](Projective_special_linear_group), PSL(n, F), are formed by taking the [quotients](Quotient_group) of GL(n, F) and SL(n, F), respectively, by their [centers](Group_center). These groups represent the induced [action](Group_action_(mathematics)) on the associated [projective space](Projective_space).

#### Affine Group

The [affine group](Affine_group), Aff(n, F), is an [extension](Group_extension) of GL(n, F) by the group of translations in F<sup>n</sup>. It can be expressed as a [semidirect product](Semidirect_product): Aff(n, F) = GL(n, F) ⋉ F<sup>n</sup>, where GL(n, F) acts on F<sup>n</sup> in the standard way. The affine group represents all [affine transformations](Affine_transformation) of the [affine space](Affine_space) underlying the vector space F<sup>n</sup>. Analogous constructions exist for other subgroups, such as the [special affine group](Special_affine_group) (SL(n, F) ⋉ F<sup>n</sup>) and the [Poincaré group](Poincar%C3%A9_group), which is the affine group associated with the [Lorentz group](Lorentz_group).

#### General Semilinear Group

The [general semilinear group](General_semilinear_group), ΓL(n, F), encompasses all invertible [semilinear transformations](Semilinear_transformation) and contains GL(n, F). A semilinear transformation is akin to a linear transformation but allows for a "twist" via a [field automorphism](Field_automorphism) in scalar multiplication. It can be represented as a semidirect product: ΓL(n, F) = Gal(F) ⋉ GL(n, F), where Gal(F) is the [Galois group](Galois_group) of F, acting on the matrix entries. The projective semilinear group PΓL(n, F) is particularly important as it forms the [collineation group](Collineation_group) of [projective space](Projective_space) for n > 2, extending PGL(n, F).

#### Full Linear Monoid

By relaxing the non-zero determinant condition, we arrive at the full linear monoid, a structure sometimes called the full linear semigroup or general linear monoid. It is, in fact, a [regular semigroup](Regular_semigroup).

#### Infinite General Linear Group

The infinite general linear group, or stable general linear group, is the [direct limit](Direct_limit) of the inclusions GL(n, F) → GL(n+1, F) (using block matrix embedding). It's denoted GL(F) or GL(∞, F) and can also be viewed as the group of invertible infinite matrices that differ from the identity in only a finite number of positions. This group plays a role in [algebraic K-theory](Algebraic_K-theory) for defining K<sub>1</sub>. Over the reals, it possesses a well-understood topology due to [Bott periodicity](Bott_periodicity). It’s important not to confuse this with the group of bounded invertible operators on a [Hilbert space](Hilbert_space), which is a larger, contractible group (by [Kuiper's theorem](Kuiper%27s_theorem)).